@page 
@model TutorialModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Tutorial";
}

<div id="initialBackendPolyString" data-poly="@Model.Poly"></div>
<div class="tutorial">
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-lg-3">
            <div class="list-group">
                <p id="FORMS-tab" class="list-group-item active">
                    Recognizable Forms
                </p>
                <p id="RZT-tab" class="list-group-item">Rational Zero Test</p>
                <p id="DESCARTES-tab" class="list-group-item">Descartes' Rule</p>
                <p id="SYNTHETIC-tab" class="list-group-item">Synthetic Division</p>
                <p id="FINAL-tab" class="list-group-item">Final</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="col-lg-9">

            <div class="panel panel-primary">
                <div class="panel-heading">
                    <h3 class="panel-title text-center">
                        <i class="glyphicon glyphicon-education"></i>Recognizable Forms
                    </h3>
                </div>
                <div class="panel-body lead">

                    <div class="recognizable-forms-content">
                        <p class="p-items">
                            The first step is to recogize any forms that can be factored
                            out of the equation.  These forms must be <em>memorized</em>.
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            Given the following polynomial:
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items" id="formsInitPoly"></p>
                        <p class="p-items">We can pull out the following forms:</p>
                        <p id="formsDisplay" class="p-items"></p>
                        <p class="p-items">Upon removing these elements, we are left with the remaining:</p>
                        <p id="formsReduced" class="p-items"></p>
                        <div class="input-group pull-right">
                            <button id="FORMS-to-RZT" class="btn btn-primary btn">Continue</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="rational-zero-content hidden">
                        <p class="p-items">
                            The next major step is to apply the <b>Rational Zero Test</b>.
                            The goal of this test is to locate all of the possible rational 
                            roots of the polynomial.
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            We can determine all possible roots in a polynomial P(x) by taking 
                            all multiples of the leading coefficient, denoted p, and dividing them 
                            by all of the multiples of the constant term, q.
                        </p>
                        <p id="rzt-p-over-q" class="p-items"></p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            By dividing each p by every q, we obtain the following terms:
                        </p>
                        <p id="rzt-pq" class="p-items">\[</p>
                        <p id="skip-pq" class="p-items">
                            The above set of numbers can be narrowed down to the following roots:
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items" id="rzt-pq-reduced">\[</p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            We have a list of all possible rational roots.  
                            Now, we are on our way to some solutions!
                        </p>
                        <div class="input-group pull-right">
                            <button id="RZT-to-DESCARTES" class="btn btn-primary btn">Continue</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="descartes-content hidden">
                        <p class="p-items">
                            The next step is to apply Descartes' rule.  This rule 
                            is used to determine an upper bound on the number
                            of positive or negative rational roots in a polynomial.
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            Descartes' rule is relatively simple.  To find the possible
                            number of positive roots, count the number of sign changes in
                            the polynomial.
                        </p>
                        <p id="descartes-poly-positive" class="p-items" ></p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            The number of sign changes in this case is:  <b id="positive-sign-changes"></b>
                        </p>
                        <p id="no-positive" class="p-items">
                            A key point in this step is to remember this is only an upper 
                            bound.  The actual number of positive roots can be any multiple of two 
                            less than this number.
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            <b id="possible-positive-roots"></b>
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            Now, we must consider the possible negative roots.  We must
                            essentially repeat the process, but for f(-x).  This means that 
                            we will be working with the same polynomial EXCEPT for any odd 
                            powers of x.  Change the sign of these odd terms.
                        </p>
                        <p id="descartes-poly-negative" class="p-items"></p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            The number of sign changes in this case is:  <b id="negative-sign-changes"></b>
                        </p>
                        <p id="no-negative" class="p-items">
                            Just like with the positive roots, we must consider the possible 
                            amount of negative roots.
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            <b id="possible-negative-roots"></b>
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items">
                            Now we have an idea of all the possible rational roots
                            - from the Rational Zero Test - as well as possibilties
                            for the number of positive or negative roots.
                        </p>
                        <div class="input-group pull-right">
                            <button id="DESCARTES-to-SYNTHETIC" class="btn btn-primary btn">Continue</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="synthetic-content hidden">
                        <p class="p-items">
                            The next step is to use synthetic division with our list of
                            accumlated roots.  The goal of synthetic division is to discover roots
                            based on whether we can find linear factors of the polynomial.  If the
                            factor divides evenly into the polynomial, with no remainder, it is a root.
                        </p>
                        <p class="p-items" id="syn-total-pos">/[</p>
                        <p class="p-items" id="syn-total-neg"></p>
                        <p class="p-items" id="syn-pos-roots"></p>
                        <p class="p-items" id="syn-neg-roots"></p>/]
                        <p class="p-items">
                            First, write out the coefficients of the polynomial and choose a potential
                            factor from the roots.
                        </p>
                        <div class="input-group pull-right">
                            <button id="SYNTHETIC-to-FINAL" class="btn btn-primary btn">Continue</button>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="final-content hidden">
                        <p class="p-items">
                            We have reached the final stage.  * MORE TO COME *
                        </p>
                    </div>

                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>





